\\nnear Gundagai, in which town she is very well\\nknown. She lived on several stations with her\\nhusband. On one occasion while she was visit¬\\ning friends a gang of bushrangers attacked the\\nplace, and in the struggle that ensued one\\nbushranger was slain. At other times Mrs.\\nJenkins and her family narrowly escaped en¬\\ncounters with bushrangers. Her memory and\\nsight are exceptionally good. She reads with¬\\nout the aid of glasses, and often goes for the\\nmails. For many years she has never missed\\nexercising the franchise, and her comments\\non present-day affairs are keen and to the\\npoint.\", \"line_offsets\": [[0, 14], [15, 29], [30, 49], [50, 90], [91, 135], [136, 182], [183, 190], [191, 209], [210, 251], [252, 295], [296, 341], [342, 387], [388, 433], [434, 450], [451, 492], [493, 539], [540, 582], [583, 626], [627, 674], [675, 719], [720, 761], [762, 801], [802, 847], [848, 893], [894, 939], [940, 986], [987, 1029], [1030, 1071], [1072, 1115], [1116, 1157], [1158, 1203], [1204, 1250], [1251, 1293], [1294, 1336], [1337, 1379], [1380, 1386]], \"sentence_offsets\": [[0, 14], [15, 29], [30, 49], [50, 190], [191, 195], [196, 209], [210, 450], [451, 547], [548, 661], [662, 768], [769, 854], [855, 902], [903, 1051], [1052, 1142], [1143, 1187], [1188, 1257], [1258, 1386]], \"num_tokens\": 205, \"num_chars\": 1386, \"quality_report\": {\"ocr_quality_score\": 0.94}}, \"ocr_hypothesis\": {\"transcription_unit\": \"A CENTENARIAN.\\nActive at 101.\\nAN EPPING RESIDENT.\\nProbably the oldest living woman in Aus-\\ntralia Is Mrs. John Jenkins, now living with\\nher daughters, Mrs. Beveridge, at Blairgowrie,\\nEpping.\\nMRS. JOHN JENKINS.\\nMrs. Jenkins IB in her 102nd year, having\\nbeen born near Campbelltown on May l8,1822,\\nShe haB thus lived through the reigns of four\\nor five rulers of Great Britain, and has seen\\nSydney develop from a village on the banks of\\n| the Tank Stream.\\nIn splto of the weight of 102 years, Mrs.\\nJenkins still enjoys good health, and is still\\nactive. At her home may be seen four gene-\\nrations together-mother, daughter, grand-\\ndaughter, and great-granddaughter. All her life\\nMrs. Jenkins has been remarkably active, and\\nin her youth she was a very clever horse-\\nwoman. She spent many years on stations\\nnear Gundagai, in which town she is very well\\nknown. She lived on several stations with hor\\nhusband. On on. occasion while she was visit-\\ning friends a gang of bushrangers attacked the\\nplace, and in the struggle that ensued one\\nbushranger was slain. At other times Mrs.\\nJenkins and her family narrowly escaped en-\\ncounters with bushrangers. Her. memory and\\nsight aro exceptionally good. She reads with-\\nout the aid of glasses, and often goes tor the\\nmalls. For many yearB she has never missed\\nexercising the franchise, and her comments\\non present-day affairs ore keen and to the\\npoint.\", \"line_offsets\": [[0, 14], [15, 29], [30, 49], [50, 90], [91, 135], [136, 182], [183, 190], [191, 209], [210, 251], [252, 295], [296, 341], [342, 387], [388, 433], [434, 452], [453, 494], [495, 541], [542, 584], [585, 626], [627, 674], [675, 719], [720, 761], [762, 801], [802, 847], [848, 893], [894, 939], [940, 986], [987, 1029], [1030, 1071], [1072, 1115], [1116, 1158], [1159, 1204], [1205, 1251], [1252, 1294], [1295, 1337], [1338, 1380], [1381, 1387]], \"sentence_offsets\": [[0, 14], [15, 29], [30, 49], [50, 190], [191, 195], [196, 209], [210, 452], [453, 549], [550, 661], [662, 768], [769, 854], [855, 902], [903, 1051], [1052, 1142], [1143, 1188], [1189, 1258], [1259, 1387]], \"num_tokens\": 204, \"num_chars\": 1387, \"quality_report\": {\"ocr_quality_score\": 0.98, \"cer\": 0.018759, \"wer\": 0.121951, \"nb_char_substitutions\": 21, \"nb_char_deletions\": 2, \"nb_char_insertions\": 3}}, \"ocr_postcorrection_output\": {\"transcription_unit\": \"None\", \"ocr_postcorrection_system\": \"None\", \"num_tokens\": -1, \"num_chars\": -1, \"quality_report\": {\"ocr_quality_score\": -1, \"cer\": -1, \"wer\": -1, \"nb_char_substitutions\": -1, \"nb_char_deletions\": -1, \"nb_char_insertions\": -1}}}","{\"document_metadata\": {\"document_id\": \"16761000\", \"primary_dataset_name\": \"overproof-combined\", \"primary_dataset_filename\": \"data/03_curated/overproof/dataset2/rawTextAndHumanCorrectionAndOverproofCorrectionTriples/allArticles.corrected.txt\", \"primary_dataset_version\": \"v1.0\", \"primary_dataset_license\": \"Very likely public domain, but not explicitly stated in original source.\", \"primary_dataset_url\": \"https://overproof.projectcomputing.com/evaluation\", \"benchmark_dataset_name\": \"hipe-ocrepair-bench-overproof\", \"benchmark_dataset_doi\": \"https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18824299\", \"benchmark_dataset_split\": \"all\", \"document_type\": \"newspaper\", \"date\": \"1931\", \"language\": \"en\", \"publication_title\": \"The Sydney Morn aid\", \"transcription_unit_scope\": \"article\", \"segmentation_origin_article\": \"primary-dataset - legacy\", \"segmentation_origin_lines\": \"primary-dataset - legacy\", \"segmentation_origin_sentences\": \"benchmark - automatic\"}, \"ground_truth\": {\"transcription_unit\": \"OBITUARY.\\nMR. ANDREW MALCOLM.\\nBALRANALD, Tuesday.\\nThe death took place at a private hospital\\nin Melbourne on Saturday of Mr. Andrew\\nMalcolm, 71, one of the best-known men in\\nRiverina, and an old resident of Balranald and\\nSwan Hill districts. He was senior partner\\nin the firm of Messrs. A. Malcolm and Son,\\nauctioneers, of Balranald. When he first came\\nto this district he became overseer of Canally\\nStation, which ran 80,000 sheep. He held this\\nposition for five years, when he became pro¬\\nprietor of the Riverina \\\"Recorder,\\\" and en¬\\ntered into the business of stock and station\\nagent.\\nHe was secretary of the Balranald Racing\\nClub for 45 years, a commissioner of affi¬\\ndavits in Victoria and New South Wales,\\nand, until his death, was coroner. He was a\\nGrand Lodge officer in New South Wales in\\nthe Masonic Lodge, and was one of the foun¬\\ndation members of the Balranald Masonic\\nLodge. The funeral took place in the Pres¬\\nbyterian portion of Balranald cemetery, this\\nmorning.\", \"line_offsets\": [[0, 9], [10, 29], [30, 49], [50, 92], [93, 131], [132, 173], [174, 220], [221, 263], [264, 306], [307, 352], [353, 399], [400, 445], [446, 490], [491, 534], [535, 579], [580, 586], [587, 627], [628, 670], [671, 710], [711, 754], [755, 796], [797, 840], [841, 880], [881, 923], [924, 968], [969, 977]], \"sentence_offsets\": [[0, 9], [10, 13], [14, 29], [30, 49], [50, 241], [242, 333], [334, 432], [433, 586], [587, 745], [746, 887], [888, 977]], \"num_tokens\": 144, \"num_chars\": 977, \"quality_report\": {\"ocr_quality_score\": 0.91}}, \"ocr_hypothesis\": {\"transcription_unit\": \"OBITUARY.\\nMR. ANDREW MALCOLM.\\nBALRANALD, Tuesday.\\nThe death took place at a private hospital\\nin Melbourne on Saturday of Mr. Andrew\\nMalcolm, 71, one of the best-known men in\\nRiverina, and an old resident of Balranald and\\nSwan Hill districts. He was senior partner\\nin the Arm of Messrs. A. Malcolm and Son,\\nauctioneers, of Balranald. When he flrst came\\nto this district he became overseer of Canally\\nStation, which ran 80,000 sheep. He held this\\nposition for five years, when he became pro-\\nprietor of the Riverina \\\"Recorder,\\\" and en-\\ntered into the business of stock and station\\nagent.\\nHe was secretary of the Balranald Racing\\nClub for 45 years, a commissioner of affi-\\ndavits in Victoria and New South Wales,\\nand, until his death, was coroner. He was a\\nGrand Lodge ofllcer In New South Wales in\\nthe Masonic Lodge, and was one of the foun-\\ndation members of the Balranald Masonic\\nLodge. The funeral took place in the Pres-\\nbyterian portion of Balranald cemetery, this\\nmorning.\", \"line_offsets\": [[0, 9], [10, 29], [30, 49], [50, 92], [93, 131], [132, 173], [174, 220], [221, 263], [264, 305], [306, 351], [352, 398], [399, 444], [445, 489], [490, 533], [534, 578], [579, 585], [586, 626], [627, 669], [670, 709], [710, 753], [754, 795], [796, 839], [840, 879], [880, 922], [923, 967], [968, 976]], \"sentence_offsets\": [[0, 9], [10, 13], [14, 29], [30, 49], [50, 241], [242, 332], [333, 431], [432, 585], [586, 744], [745, 886], [887, 976]], \"num_tokens\": 144, \"num_chars\": 976, \"quality_report\": {\"ocr_quality_score\": 0.95, \"cer\": 0.011259, \"wer\": 0.0625, \"nb_char_substitutions\": 10, \"nb_char_deletions\": 1, \"nb_char_insertions\": 0}}, \"ocr_postcorrection_output\": {\"transcription_unit\": \"None\", \"ocr_postcorrection_system\": \"None\", \"num_tokens\": -1, \"num_chars\": -1, \"quality_report\": {\"ocr_quality_score\": -1, \"cer\": -1, \"wer\": -1, \"nb_char_substitutions\": -1, \"nb_char_deletions\": -1, \"nb_char_insertions\": -1}}}","{\"document_metadata\": {\"document_id\": \"16812000\", \"primary_dataset_name\": \"overproof-combined\", \"primary_dataset_filename\": \"data/03_curated/overproof/dataset2/rawTextAndHumanCorrectionAndOverproofCorrectionTriples/allArticles.corrected.txt\", \"primary_dataset_version\": \"v1.0\", \"primary_dataset_license\": \"Very likely public domain, but not explicitly stated in original source.\", \"primary_dataset_url\": \"https://overproof.projectcomputing.com/evaluation\", \"benchmark_dataset_name\": \"hipe-ocrepair-bench-overproof\", \"benchmark_dataset_doi\": \"https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18824299\", \"benchmark_dataset_split\": \"all\", \"document_type\": \"newspaper\", \"date\": \"1931\", \"language\": \"en\", \"publication_title\": \"The Sydney Morn aid\", \"transcription_unit_scope\": \"article\", \"segmentation_origin_article\": \"primary-dataset - legacy\", \"segmentation_origin_lines\": \"primary-dataset - legacy\", \"segmentation_origin_sentences\": \"benchmark - automatic\"}, \"ground_truth\": {\"transcription_unit\": \"CENTRAL CRIMINAL COURT.\\n(Before Mr. Justice Stephen.)\\nMr McKean, K.C., Senior Crown Prose¬\\ncutor.\\nNOT GUILTY ON GROUND OF INSANITY.\\nKathleen May Beeby, 30, was charged with\\nhaving murdered her son Jack Beeby, aged\\n5 years, at Wollongong, on May 9 last.\\nMr McKean said that the unfortunate\\nwoman, who was single, was found on Wol¬\\nlongong beach after she had walked into the\\nsea. The child, who was strapped to her,\\nwas dead. The accused had been in domestic\\nservice and was in desperate circumstances.\\nHer child was subnormal, and it would be\\nsubmitted that at the time the tragedy occurred\\naccused was temporarily insane. Accused had\\nmade a statement to the effect that she in¬\\ntended to drown herself and the boy.\\nIt was stated in evidence that, accused had\\ndone war work and had emigrated to Aus¬\\ntralia.\\nDr Holloway, visiting surgeon at Long Bay\\nPenitentiary, said he had examined accused\\non several occasions since May 12. In his\\nopinion she was normal. \\\"Certainly she is\\nnot insane,\\\" he added.\\nNellie McKenzie Gray, matron of a home\\nfor the destitute and betrayed, stated that\\nshe had known accused since 1926, when she\\nwas an inmate of the home. Accused was\\npassionately fond of her son and was a \\\"won¬\\nderful mother.\\\"\\nThe jury returned a verdict of not guilty\\non the ground of insanity.\\nHis Honor directed that accused be kept\\nin custody during the Governor's pleasure.\\nMr Brian Clancy and Mr W. F. Sheahan\\n(instructed by Messrs Owen and Son, of Wol¬\\nlongong, by their Sydney agents, Messrs A.\\nJ. Taylor, William Arnott, and Co.) appeared\\nfor the accused.\\nTRIAL POSTPONED.\\nOn the application of Mr Sheahan his\\nHonor postponed until the next sittings of\\nthe Court the trial of Alfred John Dillon, 21,\\nwho, it was stated, is to be charged with hav¬\\ning murdered Cecil William Bethel McCor¬\\nmack in William-street, city, on May 13\\nlast. Dillon stood his trial on this charge at\\nthe present sittings early this month, but\\nthe jury disagreed, and Dillon was remanded\\nfor trial.\\nMr Sheahan (instructed by Messrs. R. D.\\nMeagher, Sproule, and Co.) appeared for\\nDillon.\", \"line_offsets\": [[0, 23], [24, 53], [54, 90], [91, 97], [98, 131], [132, 172], [173, 213], [214, 252], [253, 288], [289, 329], [330, 373], [374, 414], [415, 457], [458, 501], [502, 542], [543, 590], [591, 634], [635, 678], [679, 715], [716, 759], [760, 799], [800, 807], [808, 849], [850, 892], [893, 934], [935, 976], [977, 999], [1000, 1038], [1039, 1082], [1083, 1125], [1126, 1164], [1165, 1209], [1210, 1225], [1226, 1267], [1268, 1294], [1295, 1334], [1335, 1377], [1378, 1414], [1415, 1458], [1459, 1501], [1502, 1546], [1547, 1563], [1564, 1580], [1581, 1617], [1618, 1660], [1661, 1707], [1708, 1754], [1755, 1795], [1796, 1835], [1836, 1882], [1883, 1925], [1926, 1969], [1970, 1980], [1981, 2020], [2021, 2060], [2061, 2068]], \"sentence_offsets\": [[0, 23], [24, 53], [54, 97], [98, 131], [132, 252], [253, 378], [379, 424], [425, 501], [502, 622], [623, 715], [716, 807], [808, 927], [928, 958], [959, 999], [1000, 1152], [1153, 1225], [1226, 1294], [1295, 1377], [1378, 1563], [1564, 1580], [1581, 1795], [1796, 1841], [1842, 1980], [1981, 2068]], \"num_tokens\": 305, \"num_chars\": 2068, \"quality_report\": {\"ocr_quality_score\": 0.95}}, \"ocr_hypothesis\": {\"transcription_unit\": \"CENTRAL CRIMINAL COURT.\\n(Before Mr. Justice Stephen.)\\nMr McKean, K C, Senior Crown Prose-\\ncutor\\nNOT GUILT. Y ON GROUND OF INSANITY.\\nKathleen May Beeby, 30, was charged with\\nhaving muideied her son Jack Beeby, aged\\n5 j ears, at Wollongong, on May 9 last\\nMr McKEiUi said that the unfoi túnate\\nwoman, who was single, was found on Wol-\\nlongong beach after she had walked into the\\nsea The child, who was strapped to her,\\nwas dead The accused had been in domestic\\nservice and was in desperate circumstances\\nHer child was subnoimal, and it would be\\nsubnitted that at the time the tragedy occurred\\naccused was tempoiarily insane Accused had\\nmade a statement to the effect 