ship.\\nQUEENSLAND AND N.S.W. WIN\\nThe junior interstate hockey championship car¬\\nnival was begun at North Brighton yesterday. New\\nSouth Wales, Victoria, South Australia and Queens¬\\nland fielded teams, all the players being under the\\nage of 21 years.\\nIn the two matches played yesterday, the form\\ndisplayed was of a high standard. Although Vic¬\\ntoria and South Australia were beaten decisively\\nby New South Wales and Queensland respectively,\\ntheir teams fought strenuously. The South Aus¬\\ntralians, making their first appearance in a junior\\nchampionship lacked experience, particularly in at¬\\ntack. Smith, Victoria's goalkeeper, amazed with\\nhis saves against New South Wales. He appears\\na custodian with bright prospects of international\\nhonours.\\nNew South Wales beat Victoria by 6 goals to\\nnil. Smith early stopped a short corner in the\\nmatch, kicking the ball clear. He saved again with a\\nhard kick when Ryan took the ball into the circle\\nafter combining well with Davis and Leslie. The\\ncountry members of the New South Wales team\\nspeedily adapted themselves to the style of play of\\nthe Sydney men. Lucas, of Lismore,opened the\\nscoring after receiving a straight, slow hit from\\nDavis. Although hard pressed, Victoria stood up\\nwell but could not finish off its movements. New\\nSouth Wales scored its second goal after a penalty\\nfully taken by Davis with Smith fell on the ball.\\nSmith obstructed Davis in attempting to clear the\\nball, and a penalty goal was awarded.\\nStevens increased New South Wales's goals to\\nthree by showing splendid anticipation, following a\\nshort corner hit by Lucas into the goal mouth.\\nNew South Wales continued its pressure in the\\nsecond half and Dalby scored after receiving a\\npass from Lucas. Victoria then improved consid¬\\nerably, and for 10 minutes kept up a constant\\nattack, but its efforts were fruitless. Lucas scored\\nNew South Wales's fifth goal after a passing rush\\nby Davis. Stevens and Ryan and Dalby netted\\nthe sixth after a centre by Leslie from the right\\nwing.\\nQueensland beat South Australia by 6 goals to\\n1. Harrold scored four goals and Siggs and Ren¬\\ngart one each for Queensland. Jones was South\\nAustralia's scorer.\\nTO-DAY'S MATCHES\\nThe championship will he continued to-day Vic¬\\ntoria will play Queensland at 2 p.m., and New South\\nWales will meet South Australia at 3.30.\", \"line_offsets\": [[0, 14], [15, 39], [40, 65], [66, 112], [113, 161], [162, 212], [213, 264], [265, 281], [282, 327], [328, 375], [376, 424], [425, 472], [473, 519], [520, 571], [572, 623], [624, 671], [672, 717], [718, 768], [769, 777], [778, 821], [822, 868], [869, 921], [922, 971], [972, 1019], [1020, 1063], [1064, 1115], [1116, 1160], [1161, 1210], [1211, 1258], [1259, 1307], [1308, 1358], [1359, 1408], [1409, 1458], [1459, 1496], [1497, 1541], [1542, 1593], [1594, 1640], [1641, 1686], [1687, 1733], [1734, 1781], [1782, 1827], [1828, 1880], [1881, 1930], [1931, 1974], [1975, 2024], [2025, 2030], [2031, 2076], [2077, 2124], [2125, 2170], [2171, 2190], [2191, 2207], [2208, 2254], [2255, 2306], [2307, 2347]], \"sentence_offsets\": [[0, 14], [15, 39], [40, 157], [158, 281], [282, 361], [362, 504], [505, 629], [630, 706], [707, 777], [778, 826], [827, 899], [900, 1015], [1016, 1131], [1132, 1210], [1211, 1217], [1218, 1303], [1304, 1408], [1409, 1496], [1497, 1640], [1641, 1750], [1751, 1867], [1868, 1940], [1941, 2030], [2031, 2079], [2080, 2154], [2155, 2190], [2191, 2347]], \"num_tokens\": 334, \"num_chars\": 2347, \"quality_report\": {\"ocr_quality_score\": 0.95}}, \"ocr_hypothesis\": {\"transcription_unit\": \"JUNIOR HOCKEY.\\nAustralian Championship.\\nQUEENSLAND ' AND N.S.W. WIN\\nThe limlni Intctstale hockc championship car\\nmini «as bei-iin at Noilh Bilcjiton \\\\c leid-\\\", Ne«\\nSoulli Wiles Vlcloili South Austialla mid Qiicen«\\nInnd fleldid tpams nil the playeis being undei Uti\\nage of Jl -.ens\\nIn the two mutch-\\\"! playiri -iislcidai