aset_filename\u0026quot;: \u0026quot;data/03_curated/overproof/dataset2/rawTextAndHumanCorrectionAndOverproofCorrectionTriples/allArticles.corrected.txt\u0026quot;, \u0026quot;primary_dataset_version\u0026quot;: \u0026quot;v1.0\u0026quot;, \u0026quot;primary_dataset_license\u0026quot;: \u0026quot;Very likely public domain, but not explicitly stated in original source.\u0026quot;, \u0026quot;primary_dataset_url\u0026quot;: \u0026quot;https://overproof.projectcomputing.com/evaluation\u0026quot;, \u0026quot;benchmark_dataset_name\u0026quot;: \u0026quot;hipe-ocrepair-bench-overproof\u0026quot;, \u0026quot;benchmark_dataset_doi\u0026quot;: \u0026quot;https://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.18824299\u0026quot;, \u0026quot;benchmark_dataset_split\u0026quot;: \u0026quot;all\u0026quot;, \u0026quot;document_type\u0026quot;: \u0026quot;newspaper\u0026quot;, \u0026quot;date\u0026quot;: \u0026quot;1859\u0026quot;, \u0026quot;language\u0026quot;: \u0026quot;en\u0026quot;, \u0026quot;publication_title\u0026quot;: \u0026quot;The Sydney Morn aid\u0026quot;, \u0026quot;transcription_unit_scope\u0026quot;: \u0026quot;article\u0026quot;, \u0026quot;segmentation_origin_article\u0026quot;: \u0026quot;primary-dataset - legacy\u0026quot;, \u0026quot;segmentation_origin_lines\u0026quot;: \u0026quot;primary-dataset - legacy\u0026quot;, \u0026quot;segmentation_origin_sentences\u0026quot;: \u0026quot;benchmark - automatic\u0026quot;}, \u0026quot;ground_truth\u0026quot;: {\u0026quot;transcription_unit\u0026quot;: \u0026quot;LAW.\\nSUPREME COURT.- FRIDAY.\\nSittings for the TRIAL OF CAUSES.\\nJURY COURT.\\nBefore Mr. Justice Dickinson and a jury of four.\\nHART V. MONROE.\\nThis was an action of ejectment to recover possession\\nof two small cottages at Paddington.\\nMr Stephen appeared for the plaintiff, and Mr.\\nButler for the defendant.\\nThe plaintiff was an elderly female named Barbara\\nRoper Hart and her grounds of action were very\\npeculiar. After having formerly lived for some six\\nmonths with the defendant, Daniel Francis Monroe,\\nand his wife, plaintiff had executed a conveyance\\nto the former, of the property in question, in conside¬\\nration of his agreeing to provide her with good and\\nsufficient \\\u0026quot;board, lodging, and washing, for the re¬\\nmainder of her life.\\\u0026quot; In this shape the deed was\\nsigned and sealed, but at the foot of it there was a\\nmemorandum, also executed by Monroe, to the effect\\nthat if he failed at any time to execute his part of the\\ncontract, Mrs. Hart might re-enter. The plaintiff\u0026#39;s\\ncase was, that she had been improperly lodged and\\nbadly fed, but upon this point the evidence was con¬\\nflicting. There was, however, a question of law as well\\nas of fact in reference to the memorandum,\\na defeasance at the foot of the deed, which has already\\nbeen referred to. This was whether the memorandum\\nhad been executed prior to the delivery. Upon this\\npoint the evidence was not very distinct, but it would\\nseem that after the execution of the conveyance, and\\nbefore handing it over to Monroe, the conveyancer,\\nwho acted for both parties, had added it and procured\\nMonroe\u0026#39;s signature, by way of rendering Mrs. Hart\u0026#39;s\\nposition more secure. There was a great deal of con¬\\ntradictory evidence as to the habits and mode of living,\\n\u0026amp;c, of the parties concerned, which need not be here\\ngone into.\\nHis Honor told the jury that the conveyance was\\nonly completed on delivery. In the defeasance was\\nadded, about the same time that the deed was exe¬\\ncuted not necessarily at the same hour, or even on\\nthe same day, but while the transaction was still\\npending, and before the delivery of the conveyance\\nto Monroe, or to any person on his behalf - the\\ndefeasance would be incorporated in the deed itself.\\nIf, however, the deed had been completed and de¬\\nlivered, the estate would have passed, and\\nthe additional memorandum would have\\nno operation. If the jury found that the\\ndefeasance had been added prior to the\\ndelivery of the deed they would then have to find\\nwhether or not there had been the breach com¬\\nplained of.\\nThe jury found a verdict for the plaintiff.\\nHARPER V. JOSEPH L. MONTEFIORE.\\nThis was an action upon a promissory note for\\n£160 10s,, said to have been made by the firm of\\nMontefiore, Murphy, and Co., in December, 1857, and\\nto be payable at three months from that date. The\\ndefendant denied that the note had been made by that\\nfirm, The plaintiff here was Mr. Josiah Harper, and\\nthe defendant, Mr. Joseph Levi Montefiore, was sued\\nin the resident member of the before-mentioned firm,\\nwhich consisted, during its existence, of himself, of\\nMr. Louis Murphy, and of a Mr. Edward Lawrence,\\nand which carried on business as brokers. The note\\nforming the subject matter of this action had, in point\\nof fact, been made by Lawrence, and the real question\\nat issue was whether or not it had been so made in\\nfraud of his partner.\\nMr. Isaacs and Mr. Stephen appeared for the plain¬\\ntiff and the Attorney-General and Mr. Wise for the\\ndefendant.\\nLawrence had absconded from the colony in\\nFebruary last. Prior to this, and while he\\nwas still a partner, he went to plaintiff and\\nmade a purchase of goods which he required,\\nas he stated, for his uncle at Geelong.\\nThe goods having been furnished, Lawrence tendered\\nhis own bill in payment. As, however, Lawrence\\nwas already indebted to Mr. Harper to the extent of\\nsome £140 - also for goods sent to his uncle at Gee¬\\nlong - and, under the circumstances, the latter de¬\\nclined to accept Lawrence\u0026#39;s own bill, insisting upon a\\nbill from the firm. The note at present sued upon\\nwas then made, as well, it would appear, as\\ntwo others, amounting altogether to about £500. It\\nwas sworn by Mr. Montefiore not only that Lawrence\\nhad no authority to sign bills or cheques, but that,\\nduring the time Lawrence remained a partner (about\\nsix months) their firm never would give any nego¬\\ntiable paper. At the time these notes were given,\\nMontefiore\u0026#39;s firm had had no transactions with plain¬\\ntiff, except as brokers for third persons, and were not\\nindebted to him. It was also stated in evidence that\\nplaintiff had frequently communicated with Lawrence\\nindividually. The defence, grounded upon this\\nevidence, was that plaintiff must have well known he\\nwas taking a note from Lawrence in the name of the\\nfirm for Lawrence\u0026#39;s own private debt.\\nHis Honor told the jury that although a partner\\nwould have full authority to bind the firm to which he\\nbelonged by attaching its name to negotiable paper for\\npartnership purposes, he could not do this in reference\\nto private debts of his own. If, therefore, the jury be¬\\nlieved that this note was given by Lawrence for a\\nprivate debt of his own, and not for a debt of the firm,\\nand that plaintiff knew this to be the case, the verdict\\nmust be for the defendant.\\nThe jury found a verdict for the defendant.\u0026quot;, \u0026quot;line_offsets\u0026quot;: [[0, 4], [5, 28], [29, 62], [63, 74], [75, 123], [124, 139], [140, 193], [194, 230], [231, 277], [278, 303], [304, 353], [354, 400], [401, 451], [452, 501], [502, 551], [552, 607], [608, 659], [660, 712], [713, 761], [762, 814], [815, 865], [866, 922], [923, 974], [975, 1024], [1025, 1077], [1078, 1133], [1134, 1176], [1177, 1232], [1233, 1282], [1283, 1333], [1334, 1388], [1389, 1441], [1442, 1492], [1493, 1546], [1547, 1598], [1599, 1651], [1652, 1708], [1709, 1761], [1762, 1772], [1773, 1820], [1821, 1870], [1871, 1920], [1921, 1971], [1972, 2021], [2022, 2072], [2073, 2120], [2121, 2173], [2174, 2222], [2223, 2265], [2266, 2302], [2303, 2343], [2344, 2382], [2383, 2432], [2433, 2478], [2479, 2490], [2491, 2534], [2535, 2566], [2567, 2612], [2613, 2661], [2662, 2713], [2714, 2763], [2764, 2816], [2817, 2868], [2869, 2920], [2921, 2973], [2974, 3027], [3028, 3