igin_sentences\u0026quot;: \u0026quot;benchmark - automatic\u0026quot;}, \u0026quot;ground_truth\u0026quot;: {\u0026quot;transcription_unit\u0026quot;: \u0026quot;LITTLE COOGEE SHOOTING CASE.\\nPATIENT\u0026#39;S DEPLORABLE CONDITION.\\nThe case of George Leslie Miller, who is\\ncharged with shooting at Lily May Davis, in\\nJune last, at Mundarrah Towers, Little Coo¬\\ngee, was again before the Paddington Police\\nCourt yesterday, before Mr Aubrey Mowle,\\nChamber Magistrate. The hearing was spe¬\\ncially arranged to enable medical testimony\\nto be given as the doctor who had examined\\nMiss Davis at the hospital was about to leave\\non an extended trip.\\nEvidence was given to the effect that Miss\\nDavis, upon examination, was found to be\\nsuffering from a punctured wound under the\\nright armpit. On July 5 Constable O\u0026#39;Brien\\nwas handed a bullet, which had been extract¬\\ned; and also two flattened pieces of bullet\\nwhich were found in her clothing. At pre¬\\nsent Miss Davis was suffering from paralysis\\nof both legs, She would not be able to ap¬\\npear at court for at least four weeks, and\\neven then she would have to be carried.\\nTo Mr J W Abigail (who appeared for\\nthe accused), witness stated that it was not\\npossible to predict when Miss Davis would be\\nable to appear. There was a doubt as to\\nwhether she would regain the use of her limbs,\\nwhich would always be paralysed. She had\\nan injury to the spine, which no operation\\ncould cure.\\nMr Abigail suggested, with a view to sav¬\\ning Miss Davis as much suffering and incon¬\\nvenience as possible, that he attend with the\\nmagistrate at the hospital for the taking of\\nfurther evidence. It would save Miss Davis\\nbeing brought to the court.\\nMr Mowle thanked Mr Abigail for the sug¬\\ngestion, and said he would endeavour to have\\nthe suggestion carried out.\\nThe further hearing was remanded to Sep¬\\ntember 29. |\\nThe accused was in a pitiable condition, and\\nwas obviously suffering from bad health. It\\nwas stated he was under medical treatment\\nat the gaol.\u0026quot;, \u0026quot;line_offsets\u0026quot;: [[0, 28], [29, 60], [61, 101], [102, 145], [146, 189], [190, 233], [234, 274], [275, 315], [316, 359], [360, 402], [403, 448], [449, 469], [470, 512], [513, 553], [554, 596], [597, 638], [639, 683], [684, 727], [728, 769], [770, 814], [815, 857], [858, 900], [901, 940], [941, 976], [977, 1021], [1022, 1066], [1067, 1106], [1107, 1153], [1154, 1194], [1195, 1237], [1238, 1249], [1250, 1291], [1292, 1335], [1336, 1381], [1382, 1426], [1427, 1469], [1470, 1497], [1498, 1538], [1539, 1583], [1584, 1611], [1612, 1652], [1653, 1665], [1666, 1710], [1711, 1754], [1755, 1796], [1797, 1809]], \u0026quot;sentence_offsets\u0026quot;: [[0, 28], [29, 60], [61, 294], [295, 469], [470, 610], [611, 769], [770, 940], [941, 1082], [1083, 1186], [1187, 1249], [1250, 1444], [1445, 1497], [1498, 1611], [1612, 1663], [1664, 1751], [1752, 1809]], \u0026quot;num_tokens\u0026quot;: 277, \u0026quot;num_chars\u0026quot;: 1809, \u0026quot;quality_report\u0026quot;: {\u0026quot;ocr_quality_score\u0026quot;: 0.94}}, \u0026quot;ocr_hypothesis\u0026quot;: {\u0026quot;transcription_unit\u0026quot;: \u0026quot;UrtLE COOGEE SHOOTING CASE.\\n¡rATTE-T-S -.BPTiORABT,E CONDITTOX\\nTh. caso or George Leslie Miller. «Alio is\\n-»..ríiid yvltli .bootine nt Lily May Davis, iu\\nÄ«l Mundnrr.il. Towers, Little Coo-\\nli was nguiu before the Paddington Pollen\\nciurt icslerdny. before Mr Aubroy JIowlc,\\nAmber Magistrate The bearing «*na spe\\nV\u0026#39;lsllv nrmnged to enable medical testimony\\nlib-glAin, lit) tbe doctor AVIIO had examined\\n.Ml*» D»Ali at the hospital \\\u0026quot;Ans about to leuyo\\non an cAtendcd trip\\nniilcnce mm filAen to the effort Hint Miss\\nBail» np°» oimulnntton, Avns found to be\\nuigerlne fiera a puni lured Around under tbc\\nSt nrmplt On July ss Constable O\u0026#39;llrlen\\n«is handed .1 bullet, which lind boen extract-\\ned and also two flatteucó* 